textDisplay: All these ideas of extrapolating from pong to halo miss the fact that the complexity and computational requirements of increasingly realistic virtual worlds don't go up linearly, or our skill at solving them doesn't, or both.  The progress is more like an S-curve - it starts off slowly, is exponential for a while, then tails off as the low-hanging fruit is taken and the problems get harder.  People make the same mistake with AI (e.g. Sam Harris).  The problems get exponentially harder and we don't get exponentially better at solving them, at least not indefinitely.  There are also physical limits that will make themselves known at some point, as we saw with e.g. CPU clock speeds and transistor sizes.

textDisplay: Ben Shapiro's kids are going to be very socially awkward if he doesn't let them get online.  The entire social construct of children and teens exists online.  It's how they communicate and interact with their peers now, it's also where they gain knowledge not taught in school that their peers gain. It's a bad idea I think.  The best thing you can do is set a good example and treat your children just a little bit older than they actually are.  Instill then with good morals from a young age and they WILL carry it through into their adulthood.  I remember being a child (and you probably do too) that adults always talked to you like you were younger or dumber than you were.  If you treat them a little older than they are they will respect you a lot more, not just as a parent, but as a person. So I made sure to not make this same mistake when I raised my daughter.  I didn't still talk to her like she was a baby when she was 8, and I didn't talk to her like she was still a little kid when she was 12.  When I told her "no" and she asked "why not?" I actually gave her the intelligent answer, and she respected me as a person enough to know that I was making a decision on whatever it may be that's in her best interest and she trusted that.  It worked well for my family.  Yeah, the internet is full of bad images and things.  That's just part of it.  They're going to see that stuff being younger than we were, that's just how it goes...  Their peers will too.  They learn taboo at a younger age, and mostly aren't as shocked or offended by it so much as we were (because we were way older when we first saw it). textDisplay: Im actually of the opinion that we wont be going down this track. Zuckerberg is old now. He’s disconnected from young people, he doesn’t know what they want anymore. textDisplay:
why is it that nobody is questioning the fact that this very situation that we call "reality" has the same nature as the virtual reality of games and of metaverse?
People wonder "but you won't have any real relationship with another human being, there'll be no touch, no perfume, no flavor... you'll be separated from everything else"...

But all of that is EXACTLY what's happening here and now, even while we have sex. We feel separated from the universe. We are insulated and insensitive.

Those who have already tasted the experience of oneness (when you feel connected with everything, and you feel everything as yourself) know that empathy may reach an insane level of feeling other beings' feelings. So we actually NEED separateness in order to keep living in this world. Otherwise we'd feel the world excessively. All the pains and pleasures would be our own.

What to do then? I think we should at least seek the ultimate reality in order to stop taking this world so seriously. This is a virtual reality world, just like Zuckerberg's dystopia.

And yet, there are cities bigger than ever before.

textDisplay:
I don’t see what’s wrong about the choices of people to participate in it. Their choice, it’s up to you of how you think your child should be guided, don’t neglect them and they won’t find the metaverse. It’s not a bad thing if there’s new kinds of communities in the world that offer a place for those who feel disconnected from the real world, and the real world people will encounter more like-minded people as a result.

A lot will become bitter as their friends ditch them for the metaverse, but it’s not a bad thing the metaverse exposed your friendship.

And older people losing a lot of power they once had because of this information age, VR will be more than just fun & games, but real life experience without the fear of death; the younger generations will be capable of becoming so much more compared to their predecessors at a much quicker rate ever in history.

Make real life more engaging and maybe people won’t want to go into vr land, or just ban your kids from the internet so you can control their sensitive dopamine circuits to do what you want, instead of mark zuckerberg
